# How to create/use management commands

1. Add aÂ `management/commands/`Â directory to your application. Django will register aÂ `manage.py`Â command for each Python module in that directory whose name doesnâ€™t begin with an underscore. 

```python
management/
        __init__.py
        commands/
            __init__.py
            _private.py
            a_command.py
```

- Your commands will be made available to any project that includes yourÂ `app`Â application inÂ `INSTALLED_APPS`.
- TheÂ `_private.py`Â module will not be available as a management command.
- Every â€œ `command.py` â€ mgmt command is called a â€˜moduleâ€™.
- Every mgmt command must define a classÂ `Command`Â that extendsÂ **`BaseCommand`**Â or one of itsÂ [subclasses](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/4.2/howto/custom-management-commands/#ref-basecommand-subclasses).

1. Create your commands as individual `.py` files in the `commands/` directory. Write your management command by creating a class that inherits from `BaseCommand` and defining a `handle` method:

```python
from django.core.management.base import BaseCommand # imports the BaseCommand class to extend from
from app.models import YourModel as Whatever # imports your django model & aliases it

class Command(BaseCommand):
    help = 'Describe the command here'

		def ad

    def handle(self, *args, **options):
        self.stdout.write('This is a management command.')
```